<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910130-0011</DOCNO><DOCID>910130-0011.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- LSI Logic Corp.:   Fourth-Period Loss Widened   Due to $44 Million Charge</HL><DATE>01/30/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LSI</CO><IN>SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   LSI Logic Corp. said it incurred a $44 million pretaxcharge in the fourth quarter of 1990, reflecting scaled-backoperations at a United Kingdom plant as well as a decision tostop direct assembly of graphics boards.   As a result, LSI reported a net loss of $45.5 million, or$1.08 a share, compared with a net loss of $1.7 million, orfour cents a share, in the year-earlier quarter. Revenue rose33% to $184.3 million from $138.4 million.</LP><TEXT>   For the year, the Milpitas, Calif., semiconductor makerreported a loss of $33 million, or 78 cents a share, comparedwith a loss of $24.9 million, or 60 cents a share. Revenuerose 20% to $655.5 million from $546.9 million in 1989.   Also, LSI said it was writing off goodwill associated witha 1988 acquisition of a graphics board company, and ceasingassembly of graphics boards in favor of Asian subcontractors.&quot;We are becoming more of a chip supplier,&quot; a spokesman said.   LSI said the actions were intended to &quot;clear the decks oftrouble spots so that we can return to profitability asrapidly as possible.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>